The garden had never been a garden before the veil fell.

Ink‑black tendrils slipped over stone and leaf, turning every surface into a wet parchment that sighed with the weight of unspoken stories. From the crest of the marble fountain, a single filament of living ink curled down like a dark vine, its surface shimmering with the faint pulse of thought.

